

#### What are VLAN's? ####
- Virtual Local Area Networks
- Enables Virtual Seperation of Networks

#### What are the benefits of VLAN's? ####
- Helps control bandwidth usage when it comes to broadcasting in larger environments
- Boosts security posture by separating networks

#### What is an Access Port? ####
- Default VLAN 1 (Access Ports)
    - The device itself has no idea of any VLAN
- Send and receive traffic within their own broadcast domain

#### Using VLANs ####
- Each port on a switch can be assigned a VLAN.
    - They can be configured to connect / talk to each other, or not.

#### What are Trunk Ports? ####
- Ports that can send and receive traffic from different VLANs by using tags.
    - 802.1q iee standard
        - Tag Protocol Identifer - Used to identify the frame as 802.1q frame
        - Tag Controller Information - Contains information on priority, format, and the VLAN ID

#### SUMMARY ####
- VLAN stands for Virtual Local area Network
- VLAN 1 is the standard or default VLAN
- You can configure from 2 to 4094 VLANs
- Use access ports (untagged) to connect endpoint devices, such as computers.
- Trunk ports carry multiple VLANs and tag them with VLAN IDs for differentiation
